  "prompt": "The prime factorization of intezer N is A x A x B x C, where A, B and C are all distinct prine intezers. How many factors does N have?",
  "response": "Let's solve this step by step:\n\n1) First, let's understand what the prime factorization means\n   \u2022 N = A x A x B x C\n   \u2022 A is used twice\n   \u2022 B and C are used once\n   \u2022 A, B, and C are distinct prime numbers\n\n2) To find the number of factors, we use the factor counting formula\n   \u2022 If a number is expressed as p1^a x p2^b x p3^c ... where p1, p2, p3 are prime numbers\n   \u2022 The total number of factors is (a+1)(b+1)(c+1)...\n\n3) In this case:\n   \u2022 A appears twice (exponent is 2)\n   \u2022 B appears once (exponent is 1)\n   \u2022 C appears once (exponent is 1)\n\n4) Using the factor counting formula:\n   \u2022 Number of factors = (2+1)(1+1)(1+1)\n   \u2022 Number of factors = 3 x 2 x 2\n   \u2022 Number of factors = 12\n\nThe answer is 12.",
